\begin{abstract}
  India's green revolution has resulted in large-scale agricultural intensification to feed its growing population. Irrigation has been central to this transformation, providing a buffer against the variability of the South Asian monsoon and allowing farmers to grow crops in the dry winter season. Historical datasets showing the change in irrigated area over time are necessary for assessments of global and regional change and provide insight into human-environment interactions. Here, district-level inventory data about the area of 25 crop types is spatially disaggregated using historical, spatially explicit crop fraction maps and maps of biophysical crop suitability. The resulting dataset has a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes and provides a map for each crop type on an annual basis, divided between rainfed and irrigated fractions. The maps show good agreement with existing contemporary maps of crop area; however, there are no equivalent datasets providing maps before the year 2000 available for comparison. We use the Global Crop Water Model to assess the effect of the new dataset on the simulated crop water and irrigation demand across India compared with previous estimates. The dataset is associated with considerable uncertainty at the grid cell scale arising from the district-level inventory data as well as the spatial disaggregation procedure. Consequently the dataset is should be used for applications at the global and regional level rather than local-scale studies that are sensitive to the values of individual grid cells.
\end{abstract}


\introduction  %% \introduction[modified heading if necessary]
India's green revolution, initiated in the mid-1960s to achieve food security for its rapidly growing population \citep{singh_environmental_2000}, has driven large scale land use and land cover change from natural land cover and low-intensity cropland to high-input agricultural systems \citep{evenson_assessing_2003,foley_solutions_2011}. The widespread use of irrigation, which provides a buffer against intraseasonal monsoon variability and allows farmers to grow crops throughout the year, has been essential to this transformation \citep{alauddin_agricultural_2008,shukla_response_2014}. While the green revolution has enabled the country to become self sufficient in food production and supported the livelihoods of millions \citep{wada_multimodel_2013}, it has also caused a dramatic increase in the exploitation of water resources, particularly the vast aquifers of the fertile Indo-Gangetic plains in northern India \citep[e.g.][]{rodell_satellite-based_2009,gleeson_water_2012}. The pressure on water resources will intensify as the country experiences major social and economic change \citep{zhao_land_2006,james_indias_2011,elliott_constraints_2014}. Furthermore, the South Asian monsoon, which provides up to 85\% of the total annual rainfall across the Indian subcontinent \citep{turner_climate_2012}, shows increasing variability as a result of climate change and other factors \citep{bollasina_hydrology:_2014,singh_observed_2014}. Given these threats to food security, irrigation will continue to be an essential feature of Indian agriculture \citep{biemans_future_2013,smilovic_limits_2015}; indeed, irrigated area is projected to increase in the future \citep{neumann_exploring_2011,elliott_constraints_2014,haddeland_global_2014}. \\

%% \citet{gray2014} showed that increased cropland productivity in the northern hemisphere in recent decades, largely occurring in India and China, can explain up to a quarter of the 50\% increase in the seasonal amplitude of atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations observed by \citep{graven2013}.

Spatio-temporal datasets showing the change in extent and distribution of rainfed and irrigated area over time is critically important for sustainable water resources management \citep{wisser_global_2008,nazemi_inclusion_2015,siebert_global_2015}. Such datasets provide insight into the drivers of agricultural intensification, highlight areas of unsustainable exploitation of water resources and improve the projections of future irrigation requirements to ensure food security \citep{doll_global_2002,wisser_global_2008}. They are recognized as an essential input to many assessments of global and regional change \citep[e.g.][]{pokhrel_incorporating_2012,nazemi_inclusion_2015}. However, as \citet{houghton_carbon_2012} points out, the lack of historical, spatially explicit data showing the change in land use intensity is a major cause of uncertainty about the effect of the biosphere on large-scale environmental change. This is particularly the case in India where there is growing evidence that irrigation over the last 60 years has influenced the behaviour of the South Asian monsoon by changing the partition between sensible and latent heat at the land surface \citep{douglas_changes_2006,sen-roy_impacts_2007,niyogi_observational_2010}. This follows results from the Global Land-Atmosphere Coupling Experiment which identified India as one of three global ``hot-spots'' of land-atmosphere coupling \citep{koster_glace:_2006,seneviratne_soil_2006}. Nevertheless, while the basic mechanisms are understood, the feedbacks between irrigation and local and regional convective activity are yet to be determined \citep{shukla2014}, even though empirical evidence of the relationship exists \citep{singh_observed_2014}. To address these issues many Earth system models now include algorithms to represent irrigation processes \citep[e.g.][]{pokhrel_incorporating_2012,osborne_jules-crop:_2015}. However, there is a critical shortage of global and regional datasets showing the change in irrigated area over time with which to parameterise these models \citep{wisser_global_2008,nazemi_inclusion_2015}, leading to substantial uncertainty in model outputs \citep{pitman_uncertainties_2009,siebert_global_2015}. \\

Several datasets of contemporary irrigated area have been developed at global and regional scales. The Global Irrigated Area Mapping project (GIAM) produced a global map of irrigated area with a 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes spatial resolution around the year 2000 based on various data sources including Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer products and the Syst\`{e}me pour l'Observation de la Terra Vegetation (SPOT VGT) product. Separate maps with a spatial resolution of 500~m were produced for the Indo-Gangetic plains \citep{thenkabail_ganges_2005}, the Krishna basin in the Indian peninsula \citep{biggs_irrigated_2006} and the entire Indian subcontinent \citep{dheeravath_irrigated_2010} using Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) data. Land use and land cover products derived from remote sensing have a high spatial resolution and the use of multitemporal satellite imagery enables the detection of land use and land cover change \citep{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. However, remote sensing approaches have a number of important limitations for spatio-temporal irrigated area mapping. Current classification algorithms cannot reliably distinguish between specific crop types or between irrigated and rainfed crops \citep{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. The fact that remotely sensed data only specifies the dominant land use/land cover class introduces a large amount of uncertainty to the resulting maps. For example, the GIAM irrigated area map for India shows a total irrigated area that is more than double the corresponding agricultural census data \citep{dheeravath_irrigated_2010}. The classification algorithms, which must be trained on a large number of ground truth points, are also uncertain \citep{portmann_mirca2000-global_2010}. Moreover, the quality and availability of historical satellite data for India is poor \citep{}. \\

An alternative strategy is to use national and subnational agricultural census data \citep{monfreda_farming_2008}. For example, \citet{freydank_towards_2008} combined data from the FAOSTAT database \citep{FAO2015a} and other sources to create an annual time series of area equipped for irrigation at the country level for the period 1900 to 2003. This data set has been used in several global studies to quantify the impact of irrigation on river discharge \citep{haddeland_hydrologic_2007,biemans_impact_2011,pokhrel_incorporating_2012}, surface fluxes and climate \citep{puma_effects_2010}, water extractions \citep{gerten_causes_2008,yoshikawa_assessment_2014} and water storage \citep{doll_impact_2012}. The majority of these studies used a scaling factor to disaggregate the country level data to a spatial grid, a requirement of earth system models, resulting in considerable inaccuracies in large countries such as India. Recently, \citet{siebert_global_2015} developed a global dataset showing area equipped for irrigation between 1900 and 2005 with decadal time steps. The maps were produced by downscaling national and subnational statistics on area equipped for irrigation using the HYDE database to define historical cropland extent and the Global Map of Irrigated Area (GMIA) \citep{siebert_development_2005}, a map showing the area equipped for irrigation around the year 2000, to define the spatial distribution of irrigated area. Area equipped for irrigation (AEI) is useful for water resource managers and policy-makers because it gives an indication of the maximum capacity of the agricultural system and highlights areas for future development. The area actually irrigated (AAI) is usually less than the area equipped for irrigation because of land that is left fallow or devoted to rainfed agriculture in certain years \citep{siebert_development_2005}. Historical information on AAI is important because it allows water resource managers to understand how demand changes in response to variations in supply at various spatial and temporal scales \citep{siebert_global_2015}. In addition, hydrological and earth system models that simulate irrigation processes require the actually irrigated area, rather than the area equipped for irrigation, as an input variable because irrigated area is usually represented as a separate land use \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. Lastly, actually irrigated area is usually reported with the crop type, allowing a more detailed estimation of water demand taking into account specific crop water requirements. \\

This paper presents a new spatio-temporal dataset to extend and improve existing information on the historical evolution of irrigated area in India. Annual district-level inventory data showing rainfed and irrigated area of 25 crop types between 1960--2010 was spatially disaggregated using historical, spatially explicit maps of cropland extent and maps of crop suitability from the Food and Agriculture Organization Global Agroecological Zones database \citep{iiasa2012}. The resulting dataset has a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes and provides a map for each irrigated crop type on an annual basis. \\

