\noindent In all cases the raw village level statistics are compiled and aggregated to district and state administrative levels. Figure~\ref{fig:survey_type} shows that the majority of district units  in the study region are subject to a full survey based on cadastral survey information. Village level data is not usually publicly available. The Directorate of Economics and Statistics (DES), which compiles agricultural statistics at the national level, ensures that the district level inventory data collected post-1998 is freely available. We obtained this data, which shows the area of irrigated and rainfed crops for the period 1998--2013, from India's online data portal (\url{https://data.gov.in/}, Accessed April 2018). For earlier years we were able to purchase district-level inventory data from Indiastat, a commercial enterprise that collects and distributes socioeconomic data about India. This dataset shows the irrigated area of multiple crops for the periods 1950--1992 and 1998--2013. Unfortunately, however, information on rainfed crops was not available from Indiastat. Thus, we obtained an additional source of district level data for 19 States and Union Territories (out of a total of 29 States and 7 Union Territories) for the period 1966--2009 from the ICRISAT Village Dynamics in South Asia (VDSA) project (\url{http://vdsa.icrisat.ac.in/}, accessed August 2015). This data has the same ultimate source as the DES and Indiastat data (i.e. the village level statistics) but has undergone some data quality control as part of the VDSA project. As an additional source of information we obtained data from Agricultural Censuses (\url{http://agcensus.nic.in/}, accessed August 2015). These censuses, which form part of the FAO World Programme for the Census of Agriculture \citep{FAO2015c}, provide state level agricultural data at approximately five year intervals between 1970-71 and 2010-11. Considering all data sources, the data availability in district units surveyed using the first data collection method ($n=\textrm{251}$, $\mu=\textrm{47.42}$, $\sigma=\textrm{16.25}$) is higher than in districts surveyed using methods two ($n=\textrm{32}$, $\mu=\textrm{18.67}$, $\sigma=\textrm{8.01}$) or three ($n=\textrm{13}$, $\mu=\textrm{7.67}$, $\sigma=\textrm{5.52}$), although this varies at different times during the study period. \\

The spatial disaggregation procedure requires the geographical area of each district unit to be consistent throughout the study period. However, there have been several district boundary changes over the course of the study period for various reasons. During the period 1971--2001, for example, the number of districts increased from 356 to 593 \citep{kumar2009}, with a corresponding decrease in the average district size from ? to ?. However, reducing the number of district units to ensure consistent district boundaries during the entire study period would result in a substantial loss of the spatial granularity that is present in the inventory data available for more recent periods. We therefore split the study period into two periods covering 1960--1997 and 1998--2010, which hereafter we refer to as historical and recent periods. A digital map of contemporary administrative boundaries was obtained from the FAO Global Administrative Unit Layers (GAUL) dataset \citep{}. For the historical period we visually identified the location of boundary changes by overlaying the contemporary district map with district boundaries shown on an historical geological map for India retrieved from the European digital archive on soil maps (EuDASM; \citet{panagos_european_2011}). Potential changes were cross-referenced with boundary changes identified by \citet{kumar_mapping_2009}. For the recent period we identified boundary changes by cross-referencing... In both cases we manually dissolved the boundaries of contemporay district units until the resulting boundaries were such that they remained consistent throughout the respective time periods.

