\subsection{Spatial downscaling}

\subsubsection{Input data to the downscaling routine}
Maps defining cropland extent were obtained from a new spatio-temporal land cover change dataset providing annual land cover maps for India during the period 1956--2010 \citep{moulds_2016}. Maps of potential yield under baseline conditions, which show the maximum attainable yield under prevailing soil, terrain and climatic conditions during 1961--1990, were obtained from the FAO Global Agro-Ecological Zones (GAEZ) database, version 3.0 \citep{iiasa2012}. Table~\ref{table:gaez_crop} provides a list of crop types included in the analysis and the corresponding potential yield map. A map of contemporary market accessibility was obtained from \citet{weiss_global_2018}. Maps of irrigated area were obtained from \citet{ambika_remotely_2016}. All spatial data layers were reprojected to a common Albers Equal Area projection using bilinear interpolation. The reprojected maps had a spatial resolution of approximately 9km $\times$ 9km, ensuring that each grid cell in the study region had the same geographical area: a requirement of the spatial disaggregation algorithm.  \\

Administrative boundary maps for historical and recent periods were reprojected to Albers Equal Area projection and converted to raster images with the same spatial resolution as the other spatial data layers. For each time period we calculated the fractional membership of pixels to each district unit, such that pixels entirely within the boundary have a value of one while pixels which intersect boundaries have values between zero and one. The resulting series of maps were used to define the grid cells to which the district level inventory data were apportioned during spatial disaggregation. \\

