\subsection{Spatial disaggregation}
The spatial disaggregation procedure is divided into two parts. First, we establish a set of base maps for the year 2005 using a cross-entropy optimization method based on the approach developed by \citet{you_generating_2014} to produce the MapSPAM product. We use these maps as the main input to spatially disaggregate irrigated and rainfed crop areas from the sub-national database described in the previous section. \\

\subsubsection{Method to create base maps}
% ``minimizing the quantity of extraneous information imposed upon the a priori matrix to fit the marginal totals''. \\

% Cross-entropy measures the ``one-way divergence of the posterior probability distribution from the a priori distribution''... and is defined:

Following \citet{you_generating_2014}, we adopt a cross entropy approach to allocate sub-national crop area estimates to a spatial grid. The notion of cross entropy derives from the concept of information entropy first put forward by \citet{shannon1948}. According to Shannon's definition, entropy is the weighted sum of information about a random variable that is contained in its probability distribution $p_{i}, i=1,2, ...,n$, expressed:

\begin{equation}
  H(p) = - \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln p_{i}
\end{equation}

\noindent where convention states that $\ln 0 = 0$, such that a probability of zero provides no information. Cross entropy measures the difference in information content between the posterior distribution $p_{i}$ and its prior $q_{i}$, as follows:

\begin{equation}
  CE(p,q) = \sum_{i=1}^{n}p_{i} \ln (p_{i} / q_{i}) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln p_{i} - \sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i} \ln q_{i}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $CE(p,q)$ is the cross-entropy of $p$ with respect to $q$. \\% The cross entropy approach ``can be stated as a minimization problem'' in which the objective is to minimize the amount of additional information imposed upon the prior distribution $q$ in order to meet various model constraints. \\

% From You 2009: "Our production allocation problem is underdetermined with quite incomplete data, and the entropy approach is ideally suited for our spatial allocation model."

The spatial allocation model is formulated as a cross entropy minimization problem. The posterior probability distribution is the area share, $s$, allocated to pixel $i$, crop $j$, water source $l$, such that

\begin{equation}
  s_{ijl} = \frac{A_{ijl}}{CropArea_{jl}}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $A_{ijl}$ is the allocated area in pixel $i$ of crop $j$ with water source $l$, and $CropArea_{jl}$ is the corresponding total area within the district unit according to the sub-national database. With this in mind, the spatial allocation model can be written:

\begin{equation}
  \begin{aligned}
  & \underset{\scriptscriptstyle{\{s_{ijl}\}}}{\text{Minimize}} \qquad CE(s,\pi) = \sum_{i}\sum_{j}\sum_{l}s_{ijl} \ln s_{ijl} - \sum_{i}\sum_{j}\sum_{l}s_{ijl} \ln \pi_{ijl}\\
  & \text{Subject to:}\\
  & \sum_{i} s_{ijl} = 1 \qquad \forall j \forall l\\
  & \sum_{j}\sum_{l} CropArea_{jl} \times s_{ijl} = Avail_{i} \qquad \forall i\\
  & \sum_{j}\sum_{l \epsilon L} CropArea_{jl} \times s_{ijl} = IrrArea_{i} \qquad \forall i\\
  \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\pi_{ijl}$ is the prior area share, $Avail_{i}$ and $IrrArea_{i}$ are respectively the total cropland and total area irrigated in pixel $i$ and $L$ is the set of irrigated crops in the district unit. The objective function (Equation~\ref{}) minimises the cross entropy between the estimated area shares, $s_{ijl}$ and the prior estimates, $\pi_{ijl}$. In other words, the objective of the spatial allocation model is to minimize the amount of extraneous information imposed upon the prior estimates in order to meet the model constraints. \\

It is clear that the success of the model is highly dependent upon an accurate prior distribution, $\pi_{ijl}$ \citep{you_generating_2009}. We base the estimation of prior area shares on the revenue model proposed by \citet{you_generating_2014}, which is expressed as

\begin{equation}
Rev_{ijl} = Price_{j} \times Access_{ij} \times PotYield_{ijl} \times Suitable_{ijl}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Rev$ is revenue, $Access$ is market accessibility, $PotYield$ is potential yield and $Suitable_{ijl}$ is binary variable which indicates whether pixel $i$ is suited to crop $j$ and water source $l$. The prior area allocation $\bar{A}_{ijk}$ of a given crop is then given by:

\begin{equation}
  \bar{A}_{ijl} = CropArea_{jl} \times \frac{Rev_{ijl}}{\sum\limits_{i}Rev_{ijl}} \qquad \forall i \forall j \forall l
\end{equation}

\noindent The prior area share is thus:

\begin{equation}
  \pi_{ijl} = \frac{\bar{A}_{ijl}}{\sum\limits_{i}\bar{A}_{ijl}}
\end{equation}

The spatial allocation algorithm is adapted from the General Purpose Cross Entropy Matrix Adjustment (GPCEMA) program \citep{lemelin_gpcema.gms:_2013}. The original program seeks to adjust a prior matrix such that the sum of rows and columns in the resulting posterior matrix equal a set of marginal totals. In GPCEMA, cross-entropy is used as a measure of the extent to which the adjusted matrix diverges from the prior matrix. In our case, the prior matrix contains the estimated area of concurrently grown irrigated and rainfed crops such that matrix rows correspond to individual grid cells and columns refer to unique crop type and water supply combinations (e.g. irrigated and rainfed rice are treated separately). We adapted these constraints to those outlined in Equation~\ref{}. To solve the model we use the General Algebraic Modeling System \citep{} with the CONOPT solver \citep{}.

\subsubsection{Method to create maps for historical and recent periods}
Irrigated area is taken from Indiastat. Corresponding total area and production taken from ICRISAT for 19 states. Total rainfed area is obtained by subtracting the total irrigated area (Indiastat) from the total area (ICRISAT). Since inventory data for the historical period (1970-2000) does not provide information on the fraction of irrigated and rainfed in each growing season we used the seasonal fraction from the base map (2005) to disaggregate historical data to growing season. Because the district boundaries for the historical and recent periods are not the same, we took the average fraction of all cells within the respective historical district polygon. 

\section{Results and discussion}
At the national level the growth in irrigated area is dominated by the increase in irrigated rice and wheat crops, as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:crop_area_ts}. Figure~\ref{fig:wheat_irrig_area} shows the growth in irrigated wheat has occurred mainly in the north and north-west of India, particularly in the states of Punjab, Haryana and western Uttar Pradesh. The rate of expansion of irrigated wheat was highest between 1965 and 1980, during which time the irrigated area increased threefold as the green revolution took hold. Figure~\ref{fig:rice_irrig_area} shows that while the area of irrigated rice has increased over the Indo-Gangetic plains it has also expanded in other parts of the country, particularly in eastern states such as Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Orissa and West Bengal. Aside from the increase in area of irrigated wheat and rice, the main consequence of the green revolution, the expansion of other irrigated crops has been important in different parts of the country. For example, Figure~\ref{fig:sugarcane_irrig_area} shows the growth in area of irrigated sugarcane, a perennial crop, during the course of the study period is centred around western districts of Uttar Pradesh. Comparing these maps with the maps of irrigated wheat and rice it can be seen that where irrigated sugarcane is grown the irrigated area of wheat and rice is less than in other parts of the Indo-Gangetic plains. \\

