%% \subsection{Validation}
Validation of the irrigated area dataset is challenging because of the lack of independent datasets against which to compare the results presented here. The database of district-level inventory data cannot be verified because the data collected by the Directorate of Economics and Statistics is the only record of agricultural statistics in India. Furthermore, the lack of observed, crop specific irrigation data means that it was not possible to validate the accuracy of the spatial disaggregation procedure at the level of individual pixels. However, the methodology implicitly includes state of the art land cover data from the GlobeCover30 land cover product through its use of the crop fraction dataset of \citet{moulds2016}. The allocation is also consistent with district-level inventory data which provide a level of spatial resolution that would be appropriate for many applications. It was possible to compare the irrigated area maps for the year 2000 with the corresponding maps belonging to the MIRCA2000 dataset, which were aggregated to the annual level using crop calendars provided with the dataset. The MIRCA2000 allocation procedure assumes that irrigation only occurs in areas equipped for irrigation defined by the GMIA dataset \citep{siebert2005}, whereas in the present study it is assumed that all grid cells containing cropland have access to water for irrigation. Nevertheless, it can be seen that there is good overall agreement between the two datasets for the crop types shown. \\

