%   \caption{Comparison between maps of irrigated wheat, rice and sugarcane from the current study and corresponding maps from the MIRCA2000 dataset.}
%   \label{fig:sugarcane_irrig_area}
% \end{figure}

The methodology employed in the present study includes some important novel aspects compared to previous inventory-based efforts to map irrigated area \citep[e.g.][]{siebert2005,portmann2010,siebert2015}. Firstly, since it relies on district-level inventory data the uncertainty in the spatial disaggregation procedure is substantially reduced compared to similar approaches using state or national level inventory data \citep{siebert2015}. This is particularly relevant in the large northern state of Uttar Pradesh where there is substantial spatial variation of irrigation intensity between eastern and western districts. A further advantage of the present dataset is the inclusion of FAO GAEZ crop suitability maps in the spatial disaggregation procedure, which describe the biophysical suitability of grid cells to individual crops and provide a physical basis for the resulting land use pattern. This addresses one of the main weaknesses of previous inventory-based irrigated area datasets which do not consider biophysical constraints during the spatial allocation of irrigated area \citep[e.g.][]{portmann2010}. The fact that the dataset shows actually irrigated area, rather than area equipped for irrigation, means that it is more suitable for hydrological modelling applications than several previous datasets because it is directly related to the volume of water applied \citep{siebert2015}. Furthermore, providing the irrigated area of individual crops allows parameterisations that take into account specific crop characteristics. \\

The gridded irrigated area dataset is associated with a large amount of uncertainty from various sources. At the district level uncertainty arises from the inventory data provided the irrigated area by crop type and uncertainty about district-level administrative boundaries. Uncertainty in the inventory data is related to the survey methods employed to collect the data. Figure~\ref{fig:data_availability} shows the majority of States and Union Territories, including the States in northern India where the green revolution primarily took place, employ full annual surveys of agricultural variables which is the most accurate data collection of the three methods employed across India. However, despite considerable efforts to remove noise from the district-level inventory data it is likely that some remains. Quantifying uncertainty in district-level inventory data is difficult because there are no alternative datasets against which to perform a comparison. Uncertainty in the district-level administrative boundaries originates from the procedure to dissolve contemporary district boundaries to create a set of district units consistent for the duration of the study period. It is possible that some minor boundary changes have not been identified. Uncertainty also arises from differences between the perception of administrative boundaries amongst those in charge of collecting village-level statistics and those responsible for aggregating them to district and state levels. For these reasons it is likely that to some extent the boundaries used in the present study do not accurately reflect the boundaries used on the ground. \\

At the level of individual grid cells uncertainty is related to the spatial input data as well as the spatial disaggregation algorithm. Maps of crop fraction maps inherit uncertainty from the GlobeCover30 land cover product, uncertainty from the land use and land cover inventory data as well as structural uncertainty from the CLUE model itself. Maps of crop suitability from FAO GAEZ are subject to uncertainty from the GLC2000 dataset because this dataset determines the cells at the fine resolution that are considered when calculating the mean suitability at the coarse resolution. Furthermore, the suitability maps are based on soil data from the Harmonised World Soil Database which is highly uncertain over India because of the lack of local soil information. Moreover, they have not been calibrated to observations of irrigated area because no such observational data set exists. Approaches based on remote sensing provide the only practicable means of deriving this sort of data at a regional scale and there have been some attempts to classify satellite images according to crop type for parts of India \citep{singh2011}, although the data is not currently in the public domain. As remote sensing technology and processing algorithms improve data showing the spatial distribution of crop types will become more widespread. These datasets could be used to derive alternative crop suitability maps based on statistical analysis to quantify the relationship between the spatial distribution of irrigated crops and biophysical suitability from the FAO GAEZ data set as well as socioeconomic variables such as population density and access to infrastructure. While these maps could be supplied to the disaggregation procedure described above, they could also be used as an input to dynamic land use change models to simulate competition between irrigated crop types. \\

The spatial disaggregation procedure employed in the present study recognises that more irrigation will take place in areas of high biophysical suitability than in areas of low biophysical suitability. However, the assumption that the spatial distribution of irrigated area is directly proportional to the relative suitability value is clearly a simplification. Furthermore, while the assumption that all grid cells have equal access to water for irrigation is considered reasonable for many parts of India, it is highly probably that some grid cells to which irrigated area has been assigned do not, in reality, have access to water for irrigation. The methodology does not account for social and cultural factors that may influence farmer decisions about the quantity and location of irrigated crops \citep{okeeffe2015}. As \citet{portmann2010} observes, ``human decisions on crop production are based on complex reasoning that cannot be captured by macroscale modelling approaches''. For these reasons it is not advised to use the dataset for local-scale studies in which the analysis is sensitive to spatial distribution of irrigated areas. Rather, the dataset is suited to regional-scale investigations which require a general sense of the spatial distribution of irrigated crops but which do not depend on the accuracy of irrigated area shown in individual pixels. \\

The irrigated area dataset does not temporally disaggregate annual crop data to specific growing seasons. This is because different applications of the dataset will have different requirements in terms of the sub-annual temporal resolution. As a result it is possible for the total irrigated area in each grid cell to be greater than the crop fraction. This frequently occurs in northern India where multiple cropping practices, particularly rice-wheat systems, are widespread \citep{thenkabail2005}. Additional data processing could apply a temporal disaggregation procedure to generate maps at a higher temporal resolution. For example the MIRCA2000 data set used crop calendars from AQUASTAT \citep{FAO2015b} and expert knowledge to disaggregate the irrigated area of 26 crops to a monthly temporal resolution \citep{portmann2010}. Alternatively a dynamic vegetation model such as LPJmL \citep{bondeau2007,rost2008} could be used to simulate crop growth cycles based on spatially explicit input data climatic conditions, soil properties and agricultural management practices \citep{portmann2010}. Similarly the gridded data set does not separate irrigated area by source. The harmonised database of agricultural statistics provides information about the fraction of total irrigated area from different sources including surfacewater and groundwater. However, the type of disaggregation procedure employed will depend on the objectives of individual studies and, consequently, it was not considered necessary or appropriate to undertake this sort of analysis in the present study. \\

\conclusions
This paper presents a new spatio-temporal dataset showing the irrigated area of 25 crop types in India between 1956--2010. It was developed by spatially disaggregating district-level inventory data to a 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes spatial grid using maps of historical cropland extent and biophysical crop suitability. The main application of the dataset is in hydrological and earth system modelling that require spatially explicit information about the actually irrigated area to quantify the effects of irrigation on hydrological variables including groundwater level, streamflow and near-surface soil moisture, as well as to identify feedback mechanisms between anthropogenic activities and the hydrological cycle. \\

\section{Data and code availability}
The analysis was performed in the R environment for statistical computing \citep{R2015}. The set of R scripts used to perform each stage of the analysis, including data preparation and allocation of irrigated land, is provided alongside the data at the Zenodo repository (TODO: doi) under an open source licence, allowing users to follow the various stages of the analysis and modify and improve the code for their own purposes. To run the scripts users must download the FAO GAEZ data independently or use alternative datasets. Full instructions about where to place these files in relation to the data processing scripts is provided with the code. Scripts used to perform data quality control on the district-level inventory data area also provided, ensuring decisions about data quality are traceable and reproducible. \\

